{"title_page": "Allan L. Goldstein", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n|name = Allan L. Goldstein\n|image = Allan L Goldstein.tif\n|birth_name = \n|birth_date = {{birth date|1937|11|8}}\n|birth_place = \n|nationality = American\n|field = [[Biochemistry]], [[Immunology]]\n|work_institutions = [[George Washington University Medical School]]\n|alma_mater = [[Wagner College]] [[Bachelor of Science|(B.S.)]]<br>[[Rutgers University]] [[Master's degree|(M.S.)]]<br> [[PhD|(Ph.D.)]]\n|doctoral_ advisor = Abraham White\n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for = Discovery of Thymosins \n}}\n\n'''Allan L. Goldstein''' is Emeritus Professor in the Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Medicine<ref>{{cite news|url=https://smhs.gwu.edu/news/expanding-role-thymosins|title=The Expanding Role of Thymosins {{!}} The School of Medicine & Health Sciences|publisher=George Washington University|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> at the [[George Washington University School of Medicine]].  He chaired the department from 1978 until March 2009 and was awarded Emeritus status in 2013. He is an authority on the thymus gland and the workings of the immune system, and co-discoverer (with Abraham White) of the Thymosins, a family of hormone-like [[peptide]]s isolated from the [[thymus gland]].<ref>{{cite journal | author = Goldstein A.L. | year = 2007 | title = History of the Discovery of the Thymosins | url = | journal = Ann. N.Y. Acad. Sci. | volume = 1112 | issue = | pages = 1\u201313 | pmid = 17600284 | doi = 10.1196/annals.1415.045 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nGoldstein grew up on [[Staten Island]] and received his B.S. degree from [[Wagner College]] in 1959 and his M.S. and Ph.D. degrees from [[Rutgers University]], the latter in 1964. He served on the faculty of the [[Albert Einstein College of Medicine]] from 1964 to 1972, and as Director of the Division of Biochemistry at the [[University of Texas Medical Branch in Galveston]] from 1972 through 1978 before accepting the Chairmanship of the Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology at the [[George Washington University School of Medicine & Health Sciences]], a position he held for 31 years.\n\n==Research==\nThymosin \u03b11 (TA1), a molecule with immune enhancing properties, was the first of the Thymosins to enter clinical trials.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 19392576 | doi=10.1517/14712590902911412 | volume=9 | title=From lab to bedside: emerging clinical applications of thymosin alpha 1 | date=May 2009 | journal=Expert Opin Biol Ther | pages=593\u2013608 | author=Goldstein AL, Goldstein AL}}</ref> It has been approved in China and more than 30 other countries,<ref>{{cite journal|author=Tuthill, Cynthia|author2=Rios, Israel|author3=McBeath, Randy|date=May 2010|title=Thymosin alpha 1: past clinical experience and future promise|journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences|volume=1194|issue=1|pages=130\u2013135|doi=10.1111/j.1749-6632.2010.05482.x|pmid=20536460|issn=0077-8923|oclc=57215385}}</ref> and has shown great promise in the treatment of severe [[sepsis]], [[cancer]], and a number of other diseases including the potential treatment of [[cystic fibrosis]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Garaci, Enrico|year=2018|title=From thymus to cystic fibrosis: the amazing life of thymosin alpha 1|journal=Expert Opinion on Biological Therapy|volume=18|issue=sup1|pages=9\u201311|doi=10.1080/14712598.2018.1484447|pmid=30063868|issn=1471-2598|oclc=644930062}}</ref> Most recently, TA1 has been found to synergize with a check-point inhibitor and further extend the survival of Stage III/IV [[melanoma]] patients previously treated with TA1.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Danielli, Riccardo|author2=Cisternino, Filomena|author3=Giannarelli, Diana|author4=Calabr\u00f2, Luana|author5=Camerini, Roberto|author6=Savelli, Vinno|author7=Bova, Giovanni|author8=Dragonetti, Rosella|author9=Di Giacomo, Anna Maria|date=July 2018|title=Long-term follow up of metastatic melanoma patients treated with Thymosin alpha-1: investigating immune checkpoints synergy|journal=Expert Opinion on Biological Therapy|volume=18|issue=sup1|pages=77\u201383|doi=10.1080/14712598.2018.1494717|issn=1744-7682|pmid=30063847|oclc=768086347}}</ref> [[Thymosin]] \u03b24 (T\u03b24), the second of the Thymosins to reach the clinic, has been shown to accelerate wound healing and the remodeling of injured tissues.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Goldstein A.L., Hannappel E., Sosne G., Kleinman H.K. | year = 2012 | title = Thymosin \u03b24: a multi-functional regenerative peptide. Basic properties and clinical applications | url = | journal = Exp. Opin. Biol. Ther. | volume = 12 | issue = 1| pages = 37\u201351 | pmid = 22074294 | doi = 10.1517/14712598.2012.634793 }}</ref> An injectable form of T\u03b24 has been developed for internal indications such as myocardial infarction, stroke and brain trauma. Early Phase 2 trials have been completed in patients with pressure and [[Venous stasis|venostasis ulcers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090326005666/en/RegeneRx-Reports-Phase-II-Venous-Stasis-Trial|title=RegeneRx Reports Phase II Venous Stasis Trial Results|date=March 26, 2009|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> Two Phase 2/3 trials in patients with dry eye and neurotrophic keratopathy have been completed in the United States with promising results.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.regenerx.com/2018-07-16-RGN-259-T-4-Improves-Clinically-Important-Dry-Eye-Efficacies-in-Comparison-with-Prescription-Drugs-in-Dry-Eye-Model|title=RGN-259 (T\u03b24) Improves Clinically Important Dry Eye Efficacies in Comparison with Prescription Drugs in Dry Eye Model|work=RegeneRx|date=July 16, 2018|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> A third Phase 3 trial in dry eye will begin in 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.regenerx.com/2018-10-29-RegeneRx-Partner-Updates-on-Clinical-Trials|title=RegeneRx Partner Updates on Clinical Trials|work=RegeneRx|date=October 29, 2018|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> RegeneRx Biopharmaceuticals is developing an injectable form of T\u03b24 for internal indications such as myocardial infarction, stroke, multiple sclerosis, brain trauma, and peripheral neuropathy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.regenerx.com/RGN-352|title=RGN-352 {{!}} RegeneRx|work=RegeneRx|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> Dr. Goldstein's research has helped define the role of biological response modifiers in health and disease, and has led to the discovery of important new links between the [[immune system]], the [[Neuroendocrinology|neuroendocrine system]] and the [[brain]].<ref>{{cite journal | author = Hall N.R., McGillis J.P., Spangelo B.L., Goldstein A.L. | year = 1985 | title = Evidence that thymosins and other biological response modifiers can function as neuroactive immunotransmitters | url = | journal = Journal of Immunology | volume =  135| issue = | pages =  806s-811s| pmid = 2861235 }}</ref>\n\n==Academic achievements==\nDr. Goldstein is the author of more than 450 scientific articles in professional journals, the inventor on over 25 U.S. and worldwide patents, and the editor of several books and monographs in the fields of [[biochemistry]],<ref>Goldstein, A.L. (ed.), Thymic Hormones and Lymphokines: Their Chemistry and Clinical Applications. Plenum Press, New York, l984.</ref> [[biomedicine]],<ref>Goldstein, A.L. (ed) Frontiers in Biomedicine, Plenum Press 2000.</ref> [[immunology]]<ref>Goldstein, A.L. and Garaci, E., Combination Therapies: Biological Response Modifiers in the Treatment of Cancer and Infectious Diseases. Plenum Press, New York, 1992.</ref> and [[neuroscience]].<ref>Bergsma, D. and Goldstein, A.L. (eds.), Neurochemical and Immunologic Components in Schizophrenia. Birth Defects: Original Series, Vol XIV. The National Foundation, Alan R. Liss, Inc., New York, l978.</ref> Over the years, Dr. Goldstein's laboratory has been a center for the training of graduate, medical, and postdoctoral students, many of whom are now continuing and expanding his studies on the role of the thymus in health and disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=246144439&privcapId=245147913&previousCapId=245147913&previousTitle=Regenerative%20Medicine%20Solutions,%20LLC|title=Bloomberg - Javier Paino|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> Dr. Goldstein has also been a pioneer in medical education, having developed a unique series of distance-education programs presented on the Internet entitled Frontiers in Medicine.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=November 28, 2018|url=http://www.frontiersinmedicine.com|title=Frontiers in Medicine|archivedate=July 25, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725034138/http://www.frontiersinmedicine.com/}}</ref> This series of lectures and National Town Forums by leading scientists focused on cutting-edge research. The broadcasts, which were presented live from The George Washington University, began in 1997 and were a first for continuing medical education on the Internet. [[Frontiers Media|Frontiers in Medicine]] received the FREDDIE award for best health site at the 1997 [[American Medical Association]] Health and Medicine film competition in San Francisco.\n\n==Professional activities==\nDr. Goldstein was the co-founder and first President and Scientific Director of the Institute for Advanced Studies in Aging and Geriatric Medicine, a nonprofit research institute that supports research and educational activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iasia.org/dsp_about_background.asp|title=Institute for Advanced Studies in Aging and Geriatric Medicine, IASIA|website=www.iasia.org|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> He also served as a member of the Board of Trustees of the [[Albert Sabin]] Vaccine Institute<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profiles/people/1417036-allan-l-goldstein|title=Bloomberg - Allan Goldstein, Chairman/Chief Scientific Officer, Regenerx Biopharmaceuticals Inc|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> and of the Board of Directors of the Richard B. and Lynn V. Cheney Cardiovascular Institute.<ref name=\":0\"/> Currently, he serves as the Chairman of the Board and Chief Scientific Advisor for RegeneRx Biopharmaceuticals, a public company developing novel wound-healing and remodeling therapeutics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=249090&privcapId=249088|title=Bloomberg - Allan L. Goldstein: Executive Profile|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\nDr. Goldstein is the recipient of several awards, including the Career Scientist Award of the Health Research Council, City of New York; the Van Dyke Memorial Award in Pharmacology from the [[Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons]]; the Copernicus Medal from the University of Krak\u00f3w; a citation from the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|U.S. Department of Health]], [[United States Department of Eucation|Education and Welfare]] \"in recognition and appreciation of outstanding work in helping to establish a national program on Biological Response Modifiers\"; a Doctor of Science Degree (Honoris Causa) from [[Wagner College]]; the Decoration of the [[Order of Vasco N\u00fa\u00f1ez de Balboa]], in the rank of Commander, Panama's highest honor, for \"contributions directed to the preservation of human life in the world\"; the Distinguished Researcher Award of the [[George Washington University School of Medicine]], and the [[Chevalier des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques]], the highest civilian award of France. He was elected to [[Alpha Omega Alpha|\u0391\u03a9\u0391]], the National Medical Honor Society in 2007.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Thymosins]]\n*[[Thymosin \u03b11]]\n*[[Thymosin beta-4]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://smhs.gwumc.edu/ Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology, The George Washington University School of Medicine and Health Sciences ]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goldstein, Allan}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American geriatricians]]\n[[Category:American molecular biologists]]\n[[Category:Rutgers University alumni]]\n[[Category:Wagner College alumni]]\n[[Category:Albert Einstein College of Medicine faculty]]\n[[Category:George Washington University faculty]]\n[[Category:Academics from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Academics from New Jersey]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n|name = Allan L. Goldstein\n|image = Allan L Goldstein.tif\n|birth_name = \n|birth_date = {{birth date|1937|11|8}}\n|birth_place = \n|nationality = American\n|field = [[Biochemistry]], [[Immunology]]\n|work_institutions = [[George Washington University Medical School]]\n|alma_mater = [[Wagner College]] [[Bachelor of Science|(B.S.)]]<br>[[Rutgers University]] [[Master's degree|(M.S.)]]<br> [[PhD|(Ph.D.)]]\n|doctoral_ advisor = Abraham White\n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for = Discovery of Thymosins \n}}\n\n'''Allan L. Goldstein''' is Emeritus Professor in the Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Medicine<ref>{{cite news|url=https://smhs.gwu.edu/news/expanding-role-thymosins|title=The Expanding Role of Thymosins {{!}} The School of Medicine & Health Sciences|publisher=George Washington University|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> at the [[George Washington University School of Medicine]].  He chaired the department from 1978 until March 2009 and was awarded Emeritus status in 2013. He is an authority on the thymus gland and the workings of the immune system, and co-discoverer (with Abraham White) of the Thymosins, a family of hormone-like [[peptide]]s isolated from the [[thymus gland]].<ref>Goldstein, A.L. 2007. History of the Discovery of the Thymosins. Ann. N.Y. Acad. Sci. 1112: 1-13. {{PMID|17600284}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nGoldstein grew up on [[Staten Island]] and received his B.S. degree from [[Wagner College]] in 1959 and his M.S. and Ph.D. degrees from [[Rutgers University]], the latter in 1964. He served on the faculty of the [[Albert Einstein College of Medicine]] from 1964 to 1972, and as Director of the Division of Biochemistry at the [[University of Texas Medical Branch in Galveston]] from 1972 through 1978 before accepting the Chairmanship of the Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology at the [[George Washington University School of Medicine & Health Sciences]], a position he held for 31 years.\n\n==Research==\nThymosin \u03b11 (TA1), a molecule with immune enhancing properties, was the first of the Thymosins to enter clinical trials.<ref>Goldstein, A. L. & Goldstein, A. L. 2009. From Lab to Bedside: Emerging Clinical Applications of Thymosin A1. Expert Opin.Biol. Ther. 9: 593-608. {{PMID|19392576}}</ref> It has been approved in China and more than 30 other countries,<ref>{{cite journal|author=Tuthill, Cynthia|author2=Rios, Israel|author3=McBeath, Randy|date=May 2010|title=Thymosin alpha 1: past clinical experience and future promise|journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences|volume=1194|issue=1|pages=130\u2013135|doi=10.1111/j.1749-6632.2010.05482.x|pmid=20536460|issn=0077-8923|oclc=57215385}}</ref> and has shown great promise in the treatment of severe [[sepsis]], [[cancer]], and a number of other diseases including the potential treatment of [[cystic fibrosis]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Garaci, Enrico|year=2018|title=From thymus to cystic fibrosis: the amazing life of thymosin alpha 1|journal=Expert Opinion on Biological Therapy|volume=18|issue=sup1|pages=9\u201311|doi=10.1080/14712598.2018.1484447|pmid=30063868|issn=1471-2598|oclc=644930062}}</ref> Most recently, TA1 has been found to synergize with a check-point inhibitor and further extend the survival of Stage III/IV [[melanoma]] patients previously treated with TA1.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Danielli, Riccardo|author2=Cisternino, Filomena|author3=Giannarelli, Diana|author4=Calabr\u00f2, Luana|author5=Camerini, Roberto|author6=Savelli, Vinno|author7=Bova, Giovanni|author8=Dragonetti, Rosella|author9=Di Giacomo, Anna Maria|date=July 2018|title=Long-term follow up of metastatic melanoma patients treated with Thymosin alpha-1: investigating immune checkpoints synergy|journal=Expert Opinion on Biological Therapy|volume=18|issue=sup1|pages=77\u201383|doi=10.1080/14712598.2018.1494717|issn=1744-7682|pmid=30063847|oclc=768086347}}</ref> [[Thymosin]] \u03b24 (T\u03b24), the second of the Thymosins to reach the clinic, has been shown to accelerate wound healing and the remodeling of injured tissues.<ref>Goldstein, A.L., Hannappel, E., Sosne, G., and Kleinman, H.K. 2012. Thymosin \u03b24: a multi-functional regenerative peptide. Basic properties and clinical applications. Exp. Opin. Biol. Ther. 12(1): 37 \u2013 51. {{PMID|22074294}}</ref> An injectable form of T\u03b24 has been developed for internal indications such as myocardial infarction, stroke and brain trauma. Early Phase 2 trials have been completed in patients with pressure and [[Venous stasis|venostasis ulcers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20090326005666/en/RegeneRx-Reports-Phase-II-Venous-Stasis-Trial|title=RegeneRx Reports Phase II Venous Stasis Trial Results|date=March 26, 2009|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> Two Phase 2/3 trials in patients with dry eye and neurotrophic keratopathy have been completed in the United States with promising results.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.regenerx.com/2018-07-16-RGN-259-T-4-Improves-Clinically-Important-Dry-Eye-Efficacies-in-Comparison-with-Prescription-Drugs-in-Dry-Eye-Model|title=RGN-259 (T\u03b24) Improves Clinically Important Dry Eye Efficacies in Comparison with Prescription Drugs in Dry Eye Model|work=RegeneRx|date=July 16, 2018|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> A third Phase 3 trial in dry eye will begin in 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.regenerx.com/2018-10-29-RegeneRx-Partner-Updates-on-Clinical-Trials|title=RegeneRx Partner Updates on Clinical Trials|work=RegeneRx|date=October 29, 2018|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> RegeneRx Biopharmaceuticals is developing an injectable form of T\u03b24 for internal indications such as myocardial infarction, stroke, multiple sclerosis, brain trauma, and peripheral neuropathy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.regenerx.com/RGN-352|title=RGN-352 {{!}} RegeneRx|work=RegeneRx|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> Dr. Goldstein's research has helped define the role of biological response modifiers in health and disease, and has led to the discovery of important new links between the [[immune system]], the [[Neuroendocrinology|neuroendocrine system]] and the [[brain]].<ref>Hall, N.R., McGillis, J.P., Spangelo, B.L., and Goldstein, A.L.  1985.  Evidence that thymosins and other biological response modifiers can function as neuroactive immunotransmitters.  Journal of Immunology. 135:2, 806s 811s. {{PMID|2861235}}</ref>\n\n==Academic achievements==\nDr. Goldstein is the author of more than 450 scientific articles in professional journals, the inventor on over 25 U.S. and worldwide patents, and the editor of several books and monographs in the fields of [[biochemistry]],<ref>Goldstein, A.L. (ed.), Thymic Hormones and Lymphokines: Their Chemistry and Clinical Applications. Plenum Press, New York, l984.</ref> [[biomedicine]],<ref>Goldstein, A.L. (ed) Frontiers in Biomedicine, Plenum Press 2000.</ref> [[immunology]]<ref>Goldstein, A.L. and Garaci, E., Combination Therapies: Biological Response Modifiers in the Treatment of Cancer and Infectious Diseases. Plenum Press, New York, 1992.</ref> and [[neuroscience]].<ref>Bergsma, D. and Goldstein, A.L. (eds.), Neurochemical and Immunologic Components in Schizophrenia. Birth Defects: Original Series, Vol XIV. The National Foundation, Alan R. Liss, Inc., New York, l978.</ref> Over the years, Dr. Goldstein's laboratory has been a center for the training of graduate, medical, and postdoctoral students, many of whom are now continuing and expanding his studies on the role of the thymus in health and disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=246144439&privcapId=245147913&previousCapId=245147913&previousTitle=Regenerative%20Medicine%20Solutions,%20LLC|title=Bloomberg - Javier Paino|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> Dr. Goldstein has also been a pioneer in medical education, having developed a unique series of distance-education programs presented on the Internet entitled Frontiers in Medicine.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=November 28, 2018|url=http://www.frontiersinmedicine.com|title=Frontiers in Medicine|archivedate=July 25, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725034138/http://www.frontiersinmedicine.com/}}</ref> This series of lectures and National Town Forums by leading scientists focused on cutting-edge research. The broadcasts, which were presented live from The George Washington University, began in 1997 and were a first for continuing medical education on the Internet. [[Frontiers Media|Frontiers in Medicine]] received the FREDDIE award for best health site at the 1997 [[American Medical Association]] Health and Medicine film competition in San Francisco.\n\n==Professional activities==\nDr. Goldstein was the co-founder and first President and Scientific Director of the Institute for Advanced Studies in Aging and Geriatric Medicine, a nonprofit research institute that supports research and educational activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iasia.org/dsp_about_background.asp|title=Institute for Advanced Studies in Aging and Geriatric Medicine, IASIA|website=www.iasia.org|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> He also served as a member of the Board of Trustees of the [[Albert Sabin]] Vaccine Institute<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/profiles/people/1417036-allan-l-goldstein|title=Bloomberg - Allan Goldstein, Chairman/Chief Scientific Officer, Regenerx Biopharmaceuticals Inc|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> and of the Board of Directors of the Richard B. and Lynn V. Cheney Cardiovascular Institute.<ref name=\":0\"/> Currently, he serves as the Chairman of the Board and Chief Scientific Advisor for RegeneRx Biopharmaceuticals, a public company developing novel wound-healing and remodeling therapeutics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=249090&privcapId=249088|title=Bloomberg - Allan L. Goldstein: Executive Profile|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\nDr. Goldstein is the recipient of several awards, including the Career Scientist Award of the Health Research Council, City of New York; the Van Dyke Memorial Award in Pharmacology from the [[Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons]]; the Copernicus Medal from the University of Krak\u00f3w; a citation from the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|U.S. Department of Health]], [[United States Department of Eucation|Education and Welfare]] \"in recognition and appreciation of outstanding work in helping to establish a national program on Biological Response Modifiers\"; a Doctor of Science Degree (Honoris Causa) from [[Wagner College]]; the Decoration of the [[Order of Vasco N\u00fa\u00f1ez de Balboa]], in the rank of Commander, Panama's highest honor, for \"contributions directed to the preservation of human life in the world\"; the Distinguished Researcher Award of the [[George Washington University School of Medicine]], and the [[Chevalier des Palmes Acad\u00e9miques]], the highest civilian award of France. He was elected to [[Alpha Omega Alpha|\u0391\u03a9\u0391]], the National Medical Honor Society in 2007.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Thymosins]]\n*[[Thymosin \u03b11]]\n*[[Thymosin beta-4]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://smhs.gwumc.edu/ Department of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology, The George Washington University School of Medicine and Health Sciences ]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goldstein, Allan}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American geriatricians]]\n[[Category:American molecular biologists]]\n[[Category:Rutgers University alumni]]\n[[Category:Wagner College alumni]]\n[[Category:Albert Einstein College of Medicine faculty]]\n[[Category:George Washington University faculty]]\n[[Category:Academics from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Academics from New Jersey]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, added 1 DOI, templated 1 journal cites (Diberri fmt authors)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allan_L._Goldstein"}
{"title_page": "2018 Philadelphia Fusion season", "text_new": "{{Infobox OWL season\n| logo =\n| team = Philadelphia Fusion\n| year = 2018\n| record = 24\u201316 ({{winpct|24|16}})\n| division = Atlantic\n| division_place = 4th\n| league_place = 6th\n| coach = Yann Luu\n| owner = [[Comcast Spectacor]]\n| s1playoffs = ''Did not qualify''\n| s2playoffs = [[2018 Overwatch League Season#Playoffs 2|Finals]]\n| s3playoffs = ''Did not qualify''\n| s4playoffs = ''Did not qualify''\n| playoffs = [[2018 Overwatch League Grand Finals|Grand Finals]]\n| OWL allstars = {{Collapsible list\n| title = 2\n| 1 = Carpe (Lee Jae-hyeok)\n| 2 = Poko (Gael Gouzarch)\n}}\n| earnings = $525,000\n| no_prevseason = true\n}}\n\nThe '''2018 Philadelphia Fusion season''' was the first season of the [[Philadelphia Fusion]]'s existence in the [[Overwatch League]]. The team finished with a regular season record of 24\u201316, which was the fifth best in the [[Overwatch League]]. Philadelphia had the same record as the [[London Spitfire]], but London held the tiebreaker by map differential. Philadelphia qualified for the Stage 2 playoffs, in which they lost in the finals against the [[New York Excelsior]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcsports.com/philadelphia/nbc-sports-philadelphia/philadelphia-fusion-underdogs-heroes-story-so-far-overwatch-league |title=Philadelphia Fusion: From underdogs to heroes \u2014 the story so far |date=July 26, 2018 |last=Akshon Esports |website=NBC Sports}}</ref> The team also qualified for the Season Playoffs, in which they lost in the [[2018 Overwatch League Grand Finals|Grand Finals]] against the London Spitfire.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/24219415/london-spitfire-wins-inaugural-overwatch-league-title |title=London Spitfire wins inaugural Overwatch League title |date=July 28, 2018 |last=Waltzer |first=Noah |website=ESPN}}</ref>\n\n== Preceding offseason ==\nOn November 3, 2017, Fusion announced their inaugural season roster, consisting of the following players:<ref name=roster1>{{cite web |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20171103005202/en/Philadelphia-Fusion-Players-Coaches-Unveiled |title=Philadelphia Fusion Players and Coaches Unveiled |date=November 3, 2017 |website=Business Wire}}</ref>\n*Lee \"Carpe\" Jae-hyeok\n*Simon \"Snillo\" Ekstr\u00f6m\n*Georgii \"ShaDowBurn\" Gushcha\n*Josue \"Eqo\" Corona\n*Kim \"SADO\" Su-min\n*Joona \"fragi\" Laine\n*Alberto \"Neptuno\" Gonz\u00e1lez Molinillo\n*Park \"DayFly\" Jeong-hwan\n*Joseph \"Joemeister\" Gramano\n*Isaac \"Boombox\" Charles\n*Choi \"Hotba\" Hong-jun\n*Gael \"Poko\" Gouzerch\nDue to \"player logistics issues,\" the Philadelphia Fusion did not participate in preseason play.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/overwatch/overwatch-league-philadelphia-fusion-preseason |title=Philadelphia Fusion will miss the Overwatch League preseason |date=December 5, 2017 |last=Bailey |first=Dustin |website=PC Games}}</ref>\n\n== Review ==\n=== Regular season ===\nPhiladelphia's first regular season OWL match was a 3\u20132 victory against the [[2018 Houston Outlaws season|Houston Outlaws]] on January 11.<ref>{{cite news |last=Carpenter |first=Nicole |title=New York Excelsior, London Spitfire, Philadelphia Fusion impressed fans at Overwatch League day two |date=January 11, 2019 |work=Dot Esports |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/overwatch-league-day-two-20127 |access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> On January 25, Philadelphia upset the undefeated [[2018 New York Excelsior season|New York Excelsior]], which marked New York's only loss in Stage 1.<ref>{{cite news |last=Luongo |first=Cody |title=ESI Gambling Report: Overwatch League Stage 1 Playoffs |date=February 9, 2018 |work=Esports Insider |url=https://esportsinsider.com/2018/02/esi-gambling-report-overwatch-league-stage-1-playoffs/ |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Carpenter |first=Nicole |title=Philly Fusion\u2019s win over NYXL proves no one is unbeatable in the Overwatch League |date=January 25, 2018 |work=Dot Esports |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/philly-fusion-nyxl-upset-owl-jan-25-20538 |access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> With a lack of preparation time heading into the regular season, the team struggled for form in [[2018 Overwatch League season#Stage 1|Stage 1]] and would only manage to notch 6 victories, missing the Stage 1 Playoffs.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Final Standings in Stage One of the Overwatch League |date=February 11, 2018 |work=Dexerto |url=https://www.dexerto.com/news/the-final-standings-in-stage-one-of-the-overwatch-league/43920 |access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nUsing the stage-break to catch up on lost practice time and welcoming the arrival of [[Israel]]i DPS player Josue \"Eqo\" Corana, [[2018 Overwatch League season#Stage 2|Stage 2]] would prove to be a turning point for the team. After opening up the stage with back-to-back sweeps over the [[Boston Uprising]] and [[Florida Mayhem]], the team would continue to impress and go on to achieve a much improved 3rd-place finish \u2013 good enough for a stage playoffs berth.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://compete.kotaku.com/phillys-secret-weapon-shines-in-overwatch-league-debut-1823307466|title=Philly's Secret Weapon Shines In Overwatch League Debut|last=Van Allen|first=Eric|date=25 February 2018|work=Compete (Kotaku)|access-date=12 July 2018}}</ref> During the [[2018 Overwatch League season#Playoffs 2|Stage 2 Playoffs]], the team surprised many after defeating heavily favored Stage 1 champions [[London Spitfire]] in the semi-finals, however a finals match-up with the [[New York Excelsior]] would prove a juggernaut too much as the Fusion would fall short in a hard-fought 5-map match.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/esports/story/_/id/22912064/overwatch-league-stage-2-playoffs-recap|title=New York Excelsior reverse-sweeps Philadelphia Fusion to win Stage 2|last=Nguyen|first=Steven|date=26 March 2018|work=ESPN|access-date=12 July 2018|last2=Craffey|first2=Liam}}</ref>\n\nHeading into the final match of [[2018 Overwatch League season#Stage 3|Stage 3]] on May 5, the Fusion needed a win over the [[2018 Los Angeles Valiant season|Los Angeles Valiant]] for a shot to claim the 4th seed in the Stage 3 playoff bracket. However, the Valiant proved too much to handle, as they defeated the Fusion by a score of 3\u20132 and claimed the 4th seed for their own.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Brien |first=Joe |title=The Overwatch League Stage 3 Playoff Teams and Bracket are Set |date=May 6, 2018 |work=Dexerto |url=https://www.dexerto.com/overwatch/the-overwatch-league-stage-3-playoff-teams-and-bracket-are-set-76796 |access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[2018 Dallas Fuel season|Dallas Fuel's]] upset 3\u20131 win over the Los Angeles Valiant on June 15, Philadelphia needed a 4\u20130 sweep over the [[2018 London Spitfire season|London Spitfire]] in order to make the [[2018 Overwatch League season#Playoffs 4|Stage 4 Playoffs]]. While the Fusion were victorious in that matchup, they were only able to win by a score of 3\u20131 and subsequently, missed the Stage 4 Playoffs.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lingle |first=Samuel |title=Dallas Fuel will play in OWL stage 4 title matches after Philadelphia Fusion fail to sweep London Spitfire |date=June 16, 2018 |work=Dot Esports |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/philadelphia-fusion-dallas-fuel-stage-four-title-matches-owl-24924 |access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Season playoffs ===\nPhiladelphia Fusion claimed the 6th seed in the Season Playoffs on June 15, after [[2018 Seoul Dynasty season|Seoul Dynasty]] lost to the [[2018 Los Angeles Gladiators season|Los Angeles Gladiators]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Lingle |first=Samuel |title=Seoul Dynasty\u2019s loss cedes an OWL playoff spot to Philadelphia Fusion |date=June 15, 2018 |work=Dot Esports |url=https://dotesports.com/overwatch/news/seoul-dynasty-eliminated-owl-playoffs-24898 |access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> During the Post-Season Playoffs, Philadelphia Fusion first faced the Boston Uprising. After a dominant first game they lost the second one, forcing a tie-breaker game which Fusion managed to win. After that they faced the New York Excelsior, who were heavy favorites to win the Post-Season playoffs. Fusion upset them in the first game, winning 3\u20130 and then narrowly winning the second game 3\u20132, which sent them to the grand finals. In the Grand Finals they faced another underdog; the London Spitifire. The Spitfire however showed the potential their team had and beat the Fusion in a best of 3 game series, winning 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite news |last=Waltzer |first=Noah |title=London Spitfire wins inaugural Overwatch League title |publisher=ESPN |date=28 July 2018 |url=http://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/24219415/london-spitfire-wins-inaugural-overwatch-league-title |access-date=18 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bright |first=Ryan |title=London Spitfire duo master Philadelphia Fusion to claim first Overwatch League title |date=28 July 2018 |publisher=NBC Sports |url=https://www.nbcsports.com/philadelphia/nbc-sports-philadelphia/london-spitfire-duo-master-philadelphia-fusion-claim-first-overwatch-league |access-date=18 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Final roster ==\n{{OWL roster header|team=Philadelphia Fusion|season=2018}}\n<!-- list of players -->\n{{OWL player | num = 3 | handle = snillo | first = Simon | last = Ekstr\u00f6m | role = Damage | nat=SWE | prev_team=123}}\n{{OWL player | num = 13 | handle = ShaDowBurn | first = Georgii | last = Gushcha | role = Damage | nat=RUS | prev_team=[[FaZe Clan]]}}\n{{OWL player | num = 15 | handle = Eqo | first = Josue | last = Corona | role = Damage | nat=Israel | prev_team=Zengaming eSports}}\n{{OWL player | num = 18 | handle = Carpe | name = Lee Jae-hyeok | role = Damage | nat=KOR | prev_team=[[FaZe Clan]]}}\n{{OWL player | num = 9 | handle = SADO | name = Kim Su-min | role = Tank | nat=KOR | prev_team=''N/A''}}\n{{OWL player | num = 54 | handle = Fragi | first = Joona | last = Laine | role = Tank | nat=FIN | prev_team=Team Gigantti}}\n{{OWL player | num = 8 | handle = neptuNo | first = Alberto | last = Gonz\u00e1lez | role = Support | nat=ESP | prev_team=[[Cloud9|Cloud9 EU]]}}\n{{OWL player | num = 10 | handle = DayFly | name = Park Jeong-hwan | role = Support | nat=KOR | prev_team=Ardeont}}\n{{OWL player | num = 23 | handle = Joemeister | first = Joseph | last = Gramano | role = Support | nat=CAN | prev_team=[[FaZe Clan]]}}\n{{OWL player | num = 42 | handle = Boombox | first = Isaac | last = Charles | role = Support | nat=ENG | prev_team=eUnited}}\n{{OWL player | num = 7 | handle = HOTBA | name = Choi Hong-jun | role = Flex | nat=KOR | prev_team=LW Red}}\n{{OWL player | num = 21 | handle = Poko | first = Gael | last = Gouzerch | role = Flex | nat=FRA | prev_team=GamersOrigin}}\n<!--end of list players-->\n{{OWL roster footer\n| head_coach =\n*Yann Luu\n| roster_url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180802052746/https://overwatchleague.com/en-us/players\n| accessdate = November 3, 2017\n}}\n\n== Standings ==\n=== Record by stage ===\n{| class=\"toccolours\" border=0 cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"font-size:95%; text-align:left; width:700px;\"\n|- align=\"left\" style=\"background:#{{OWL color|PHI|1}}; color:#{{OWL color|PHI|2}};\"\n! style=\"width:75px\" | Stage !! {{abbr|Pld|Matches played}} !! {{abbr|W|Wins}} !! {{abbr|L|Losses}} !! {{abbr|Pct|Winning percentage}} !! {{abbr|MW|Maps won}} !! {{abbr|ML|Maps lost}} !! {{abbr|MT|Maps tied}} !! {{abbr|MD|Map differential}} !! {{abbr|Pos|Position in league}}\n|-\n|colspan = \"10\" |\n|-\n| 1 || 10 || 6 || 4 || {{winpct|6|4}} || 20 || 24 || 1 || -4 || 7\n|-style=\"background:#cfc\"\n| 2 || 10 || 7 || 3 || {{winpct|7|3}} || 27 || 15 || 0 || +12 || 3\n|-\n| 3 || 10 || 5 || 5 || {{winpct|5|5}} || 24 || 23 || 0 || +1 || 7\n|-\n| 4 || 10 || 6 || 4 || {{winpct|6|4}} || 22 || 18 || 1 || +4 || 6\n|-style=\"background-co